# By-default we take the name of this file as .env only because it is a convention to use .env file for storing environment variables in a project. The .env file is a simple text file that contains key-value pairs of environment variables. It is used to store sensitive information such as database credentials, API keys, and other configuration settings that should not be hard-coded in the source code. By using a .env file, we can keep our sensitive information secure and easily manage different configurations for different environments (development, testing, production) without changing the source code.

# .env file :-
# A .env file is a simple text file that contains environment variables for your application. It is used to store configuration settings and sensitive information (like API keys, database URLs, etc.) in a secure and organized way. The .env file is typically placed in the root directory of your project and is not committed to version control (e.g., Git) to keep sensitive data private.
# The dotenv package is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a .env file into process.env. This allows you to access your configuration settings and sensitive information in your Node.js application without hardcoding them in your source code. It’s especially useful for managing different configurations for development, testing, and production environments.
# To use dotenv, you first need to install it using npm: npm install dotenv
# And we never commit or upload this .env file to github or any version control system as it contains sensitive information like API keys, database URLs, etc. So we will add this .env file in our .gitignore file to ignore it from being committed to version control. This way, we can keep our sensitive information secure and prevent it from being exposed publicly.

# THis file stores anything in a fixed format which is :- KEY=VALUE, where KEY is the name of the environment variable and VALUE is the value of that environment variable. We can have multiple lines in this .env file, each line containing a different environment variable. For example:
# DB_URL=mongodb://localhost:27017/mydatabase   

# Generally we take name of KEY in uppercase letters and we can use underscores to separate words in the KEY for better readability. The VALUE can be a string, number, boolean, or any other data type depending on the context of the environment variable. We can also have comments in the .env file by starting a line with a # symbol. Comments are ignored by the dotenv package when loading the environment variables.
# And we don't add any spaces or quotes around the = sign in the KEY=VALUE pairs in the .env file, as it can cause issues when loading the environment variables. So we should write it like this: KEY=VALUE, without any spaces around the = sign.

# Once environmental variables gets saved in .env file, then we can use them anywhere in our project.
# But we can't use these environment variables directly in our code, we need to load them into our application using the dotenv package. To do that, we need to require the dotenv package and call the config() method at the very beginning of our application (usually in the app.js file) before any other code that uses environment variables. This will load the environment variables from the .env file into process.env, allowing us to access them throughout our application using process.env.KEY_NAME.

# We use this .env file only in development phase and not in production phase (i.e when users can access our application) because in production phase, we usually set environment variables directly on the server or hosting platform where our application is deployed, rather than using a .env file. This is because .env files are not secure for production environments as they can be easily accessed by unauthorized users if not handled properly. In production, we typically use environment variables that are set at the system level or through the hosting platform's configuration settings to keep sensitive information secure.


# Here this is the connection string for our MongoDB Atlas database. We will store this connection string in this .env file as well because it contains sensitive information such as the username and password for our database, and we don't want to expose it publicly. So we will store it in this .env file and then we will load it in our application using the dotenv package, so that we can use this connection string to connect to our MongoDB Atlas database and perform CRUD operations on our database.
# This connection string is required to connect to our MongoDB Atlas database and to perform CRUD operations on our database. It contains the username and password for our database, as well as the cluster information and other parameters required to establish a connection to the database.
# It is actually the cloud version of MongoDB database, which is provided by MongoDB Atlas. It allows us to host our database in the cloud and access it from anywhere in the world, without having to set up and maintain our own database server. This way, we can focus on developing our application without worrying about the database management and maintenance.
